column1: The President still has not said if he has tested negative yet still wants to invite hundreds of people to the site of a COVID-19 hotspot. This is reckless and DANGEROUS. https://t.co/lMOPNhb3IM

We often think of mental health as an isolated issue but it's not. Stress from COVID-19 racial injustice homelessness election unemployment & more all play a role. Our recovery as a state & nation will rely on our mental health as well as our physical & economic well-being.

Last call to vote in the August Primary! We're lucky to live in a state where you don't need to wait in line to vote take the day off of work risk exposure to COVID-19 or even find a stamp to #VoteByMail. No excuses WA - let's get those votes in dropboxes or postmarked by 8pm!

I would love nothing more than to be marching in one of our #4thofJuly parades this weekend with neighbors & family but I know the health of those around us is far more important. It’s our patriotic duty to stop the spread of #COVID19 & save lives.  #TBT 2018 #CelebrateKirkland https://t.co/gM3VHYUele

We may be separated by social distance but I had a great time w/ Rock the Ride & @Mike_CA05 this morning to continue the fight to end gun violence supporting @GiffordsCourage @Everytown & @AlainasVoice🧡Inspiring to be in this fight with all across the country! #RTRvirtual2020 https://t.co/jvwuzYHHG2
Too many Americans have already lost a job due to COVID-19. We can’t afford to lose any more. That’s why my priority of a jobs protection plan was included in the Heroes relief package. (1/2)

Even if you are young and healthy it is incredibly important to practice social distancing. You could be a carrier for #COVID19 and unknowingly spread it to the most vulnerable in our community. https://t.co/2MudlTIkm0
Please continue to follow the @CDCgov and @WHO (World Health Organization) for the most up-to-date and accurate information. #COVID19 (9/9)  https://t.co/FHRAnNZ82v

Combating this pandemic will take all of us working together to support the most vulnerable in our community. I will continue to do everything I can to provide resources to Washington State and across the country.  #COVID19  (8/9)

🏃‍♀️ Run errands - Our elderly family friends and neighbors will need help in the coming weeks if they are unable to go out in the community to run every day errands like picking up prescriptions or milk.  #COVID19 (7/9)

👶 Provide childcare - With schools in our region closing for at least 6 weeks many parents are going to be struggling. If you are healthy and able please consider providing childcare to neighbors who don't have the option to work from home.  #COVID19 (6/9)
💵 Give to local charities - Many nonprofit organizations are in the swing of their yearly fundraising campaigns and have had to cancel large events that they depend on.  #COVID19 (5/9)

🛍 Shop small - Our small businesses and restaurants are suffering the most with many already being forced to close their doors due to an 80% or more drop in sales. Order takeout if you don't feel comfortable going out or buy gift cards for your local shops. #COVID19 (4/9)

🧻 Donate supplies - Our local homeless shelters will be overextended and will be running out of supplies as the pandemic continues. Consider donating the extra supplies you stocked up on and don't need at home. #COVID19 (3/9)
🍎 Donate food/time - Food banks in our area have seen a dramatic drop in donations and volunteers. Most volunteers are 60+ and in the higher risk category. #COVID19 (2/9)

Wondering what you can do to help in your community with #COVID19 response and relief? Here are some ideas (thread):  💉 Donate blood - Our local blood banks are at critically low reserves due to blood drive cancellations. (1/9)  https://t.co/HXgtOfOfOy

A special #InternationalWomensDay shoutout to Lupe Hernandez who in 1966 invented hand sanitizer. As we continue to fight the spread of #COVID19 let's be sure to thank the women who came before and the ones on the front line of the crisis today.  #IWD2020 https://t.co/jC5CbrxTpO
